            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Paul Koval\u2019s hands, calloused and mapped with faint scars, tell the story of a life built, not inherited. Raised in a working-class neighborhood in Pittsburgh, he was the son of a steel mill worker who taught him that value came from what you could create yourself. While his peers saw college as the only way out of the Rust Belt\u2019s decline, Paul found his classroom in his father\u2019s garage, learning the language of wood, grain, and tools. He was a competent but disinterested student, graduating high school with a diploma but a much richer education in practical skills.\n\nHis turning point came not in a classroom, but in the dusty wings of a struggling local playhouse. Hired for a cheap, one-off job to build a set of stairs, Paul was mesmerized. He discovered that his knack for joinery and framing could conjure not just houses, but enchanted forests and gritty 1940s New York apartments. He had found his calling.\n\nIn his mid-twenties, drawn by the vibrant and experimental arts scene, Paul moved to San Francisco with little more than a duffel bag and a well-worn toolbox. He started as a stagehand, taking any job he could find, gradually earning a reputation for his meticulous work and uncanny ability to solve complex structural puzzles on a shoestring budget. For the last fifteen years, he has been the Master Carpenter for a respected mid-sized theater company downtown.\n\nPaul\u2019s life is anchored by routine and craft. He lives in a small, rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond, its walls adorned with framed playbills from his favorite shows. His day begins before dawn with the rumble of the 38-Geary bus, which he rides to the theater\u2019s workshop. There, amidst the smell of sawdust and paint, he translates a director\u2019s vision into physical reality. A long-term partnership dissolved nearly a decade ago, leaving a quiet space in his life that he\u2019s since filled with his work and a tight-knit circle of theater colleagues.\n\nAt 49, Paul\u2019s ambitions are less about climbing and more about legacy. He dreams of designing and building a set for a show that gets a major award, not for his own glory, but for the validation of his craft. He hopes to mentor a promising young apprentice, passing on the skills his father gave him. He is a man content in his niche, finding profondes meaning in making magic tangible, one perfectly cut piece of wood at a time."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the sting of his father\u2019s hand stopping his own when he was sixteen, impatiently forcing a saw through a piece of oak. \u201cListen to it,\u201d his dad had said, his voice low and dusty. \u201cThe wood tells you how it wants to be cut.\u201d In that moment, Paul understood that this wasn't just labor; it was a conversation. That single lesson in the Pittsburgh garage became the foundation of his entire craft, a quiet respect for the material that guides every measurement and cut he makes today.\n\n2.\nIt was just a cheap set of stairs for a struggling playhouse, a job he took for fifty bucks in his early twenties. But then he saw the actress, playing a heartbroken mother, slowly descend them under a single spotlight. His plain pine and plywood weren't just a structure anymore; they were part of her grief, holding the weight of the story. He felt a jolt, a profound sense of purpose. He wasn't just building things; he was building worlds. That night, his future was decided.\n\n3.\nHis first night in San Francisco, the city fog felt like a wet blanket. From the bare window of his tiny Richmond flat, the alien groan of a foghorn replaced the familiar sounds of Pittsburgh. He sat on his duffel bag, his hand resting on the worn leather handle of his father\u2019s toolbox. It felt like the only real thing he owned. He wasn\u2019t scared, but humbled. This vast, indifferent city would demand everything, and he vowed to answer with the steady, honest work of his hands.\n\n4.\nHe remembers the morning after his partnership ended, nearly a decade ago. The apartment was deafeningly silent; the space on the counter where the other coffee mug should have been felt like a crater. Not knowing what else to do with his hands, he went to the workshop hours early. There, the familiar scent of sawdust and the hum of the table saw offered a sanctuary. He learned then that while a life could be unbuilt overnight, his craft was a foundation that would always hold him.\n\n5.\nFive years ago, a director wanted a collapsing tenement wall\u2014one that could reset in under a minute. The designers were stumped. Paul spent a week sketching, recalling his father's lessons on counterweights. He built a system of hidden pulleys and ropes. On opening night, the wall crumbled with terrifying, beautiful precision. Hearing the audience gasp, he felt no need for applause, just a deep, quiet satisfaction. He had solved the puzzle. He had made the magic real, and that was his reward."
